    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Field Trip to the City</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by high school senior Rebecca Rice says resumption of field trips is perfect example of how New Yorkers are moving on in aftermath of terrorist attack (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Schools to Resume Field Trips'' (news article, Nov. 1):</p>
        <p>The resumption of school field trips is a perfect example of the way in which New Yorkers are moving on.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Schools to Resume Field Trips'' (news article, Nov. 1):</p>
        <p>The resumption of school field trips is a perfect example of the way in which New Yorkers are moving on.</p>
        <p>As a senior at Bishop Ford High School in Brooklyn, I often take trips into Manhattan by subway. My first field trip back into the city after the Sept. 11 attacks was a big step for me, as I am sure it has been for many.</p>
        <p>Stepping out of the train station and looking up at the buildings makes you realize that life in New York has gone on.</p>
        <p>As long as teachers use discretion in planning these field trips, I see no reason that children should be denied the educational experiences they had grown accustomed to.</p>
        <p>REBECCA RICE  Brooklyn, Nov. 6, 2001</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
